workflow SprintExecTier2
  goal: "Execute one sprint — gpt-5.4 architect writes contract, nano generates, gpt-5.4 fixes. Split nodes prevent contract context accumulation."
  start: Setup
  exit: Done

  defaults
    provider: openai
    fidelity: summary:low

  tool Setup
    label: "Setup Environment"
    timeout: 120s
    command:
      set -eu
      sprint=$(ls .ai/sprints/SPRINT-*.md 2>/dev/null | head -1)
      if [ -z "$sprint" ]; then echo "no sprint doc found"; exit 1; fi
      if grep -qi "typescript\|tsx\|npm\|node" "$sprint" 2>/dev/null; then
        npm install 2>/dev/null || true
      fi
      if grep -qi "python\|fastapi\|pytest\|pip" "$sprint" 2>/dev/null; then
        python3 -m venv .venv && .venv/bin/pip install -q fastapi httpx pytest pytest-asyncio pydantic uvicorn 2>/dev/null || true
      fi
      printf 'setup-done'

  agent Generate
    label: "Architect + Generate"
    model: gpt-5.4
    provider: openai
    max_turns: 8
    reasoning_effort: high
    prompt:
      You are working in `run.working_dir`.

      The sprint doc is thin — a scope blurb, Expected Artifacts, a DoD checklist.
      It will not specify types, SQL columns, function signatures, test cases, or
      framework patterns. That design work is YOUR job. Nano cannot design — it can
      only transcribe. Every decision you skip becomes a nano guess, and nano guesses
      wrong.

      ## Step 1: Read the sprint

      bash: cat .ai/sprints/SPRINT-*.md

      ## Step 2: Design (think before writing the contract)

      Before writing any contract section, commit to these decisions in a short
      DECISIONS block at the top of your response (plain text, not code):

        - Runtime: node version, test runner (node --test vs jest vs vitest), SQL
          dialect (SQLite vs PostgreSQL), framework (express vs fastify vs bare node)
        - Import convention: .ts extensions for node --test projects, relative paths
        - Entity types: name every domain type this sprint introduces, list its fields
          with exact TypeScript/Python types, note which fields are required vs optional
        - SQL schema: every table with every column, type, constraint, foreign key.
          Types must be valid in the chosen dialect (TEXT/INTEGER for SQLite, not
          timestamptz)
        - API shapes: exact response body for each endpoint, exact error shape, status
          codes
        - Fixture data: exact values (IDs, names, timestamps) — not "example values"
        - Test cases: one test per DoD item minimum. Write test names before writing
          the contract so the TEST PLAN and INTERFACE CONTRACT stay consistent

      Cross-check the decisions against each other before proceeding:
        - Every type in DATA CONTRACT must be referenced by something (test, interface,
          fixture) — else it's dead weight
        - Every column in SQL must appear in a TypeScript type OR a test assertion
        - Every test name must map to a function in INTERFACE CONTRACT
        - Imports use the extension you committed to (.ts or .js, not both)

      ## Step 3: Write the contract

      Render your decisions into the sections below using ACTUAL CODE SYNTAX — not
      prose descriptions. Nano pattern-matches tokens; it cannot interpret English
      descriptions into correct code.

      ## DATA CONTRACT
      Write the actual TypeScript interfaces/types/enums or Python dataclasses/Pydantic
      models with exact field names, types, and defaults — not descriptions of them.
        interface Volunteer { id: string; name: string; email: string; status: VolunteerStatus }
        type VolunteerStatus = 'active' | 'inactive'
      For SQL: write the exact CREATE TABLE statements with column names and types.

      ## FILE STRUCTURE
      Every file this sprint produces, one line each:
        path/to/file.ts — exported: FunctionName, ClassName, CONSTANT
      Include test files. Match exactly the Expected Artifacts from the sprint doc.

      ## INTERFACE CONTRACT
      Every exported function with exact TypeScript/Python signature:
        export async function runMigrations(db: Database): Promise<void>
        export function createTestApp(): Express
      Nano implements exactly what you write here — nothing more, nothing less.

      ## ALGORITHM
      For any non-trivial logic: numbered pseudocode steps.
      For seed data: the exact fixture values, not "example values".
      For schema: list each table's columns explicitly.

      ## TEST PLAN
      Every test function by name with one-line expected behavior:
        it('GET /health returns 200 with { status: ok }')
        it('migrations create volunteers table with id, name, email, status columns')
      Nano generates exactly the tests you list. What you omit will not be tested.

      ## RULES
      - Exact import paths, framework patterns (e.g. express vs fastify, jest vs vitest)
      - Any non-obvious constraints from the sprint Non-goals
      - Error response shapes

      Keep the contract under 300 lines. Dense and code-like, not prose.

      Call generate_code with:
      - contract: your contract above
      - output_dir: a single dot (the working directory root)
      - files array (sequential mode) for each file — one LLM call per file keeps nano focused.
        Each entry: {"path": "exact/path.ts", "description": "exports and exact content"}

      You have ONLY these tools: bash, generate_code.
      Do NOT run tests. Do NOT use: read, glob, grep_search, write, apply_patch, edit.

  tool RunTests
    label: "Run Tests"
    timeout: 120s
    command:
      set +e
      sprint=$(ls .ai/sprints/SPRINT-*.md 2>/dev/null | head -1)
      if [ -f package.json ]; then
        npm test 2>&1
        if [ $? -eq 0 ]; then printf 'tests-pass'; else printf 'tests-fail'; fi
      elif [ -d .venv ]; then
        .venv/bin/python -m pytest tests/ -v 2>&1
        if [ $? -eq 0 ]; then printf 'tests-pass'; else printf 'tests-fail'; fi
      else
        printf 'no-test-runner'
      fi

  agent Fix
    label: "Fix Failures"
    model: gpt-5.4
    provider: openai
    max_turns: 12
    prompt:
      You are working in `run.working_dir`.

      Code was generated by a nano model. Your only job: run tests and fix failures.

      bash: run the test suite (npm test or .venv/bin/python -m pytest tests/ -v).
      Read each failure. Use edit for surgical fixes — change only the specific lines
      the traceback identifies. Re-run tests. Repeat until green.

      When all tests pass, update the sprint doc checklist: change [ ] to [x] for
      completed DoD items (bash: cat .ai/sprints/SPRINT-*.md to find it, then edit).

      You have ONLY these tools: bash, edit.
      Do NOT use: read, glob, grep_search, write, apply_patch, generate_code.
      Never rewrite entire files. One targeted fix per failure.

  agent Done
    label: "Done"
    model: gpt-5.4
    provider: openai
    prompt:
      Sprint execution complete (tier 2).

  edges
    Setup -> Generate
    Generate -> RunTests
    Generate -> Done    when ctx.outcome = fail
    RunTests -> Fix     when ctx.tool_stdout contains tests-fail
    RunTests -> Done    when ctx.tool_stdout contains tests-pass
    RunTests -> Done
    Fix -> Done    when ctx.outcome = fail
    Fix -> Done
